[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Much of the Node.js core API is built around an idiomatic asynchronous event-driven architecture in which certain kinds of objects (called "emitters") emit named events that cause `Function` objects ("listeners") to be called.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For instance: a `net.Server` object emits an event each time a peer connects to it; a `fs.ReadStream` emits an event when the file is opened; a stream emits an event whenever data is available to be read.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] All objects that emit events are instances of the `EventEmitter` class.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] These objects expose an `eventEmitter.on()` function that allows one or more functions to be attached to named events emitted by the object.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Typically, event names are camel-cased strings but any valid JavaScript property key can be used.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] When the `EventEmitter` object emits an event, all of the functions attached to that specific event are called *synchronously*.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Any values returned by the called listeners are *ignored* and discarded.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The following example shows a simple `EventEmitter` instance with a single listener.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `eventEmitter.emit()` method allows an arbitrary set of arguments to be passed to the listener functions.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `EventEmitter` calls all listeners synchronously in the order in which they were registered.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This ensures the proper sequencing of events and helps avoid race conditions and logic errors.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Using the `eventEmitter.once()` method, it is possible to register a listener that is called at most once for a particular event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] When an error occurs within an `EventEmitter` instance, the typical action is for an `'error'` event to be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] These are treated as special cases within Node.js.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] To guard against crashing the Node.js process the `domain` module can be used.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `captureRejections` option in the `EventEmitter` constructor or the global setting change this behavior, installing a `.then(undefined, handler)` handler on the `Promise`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `'error'` events that are generated by the `captureRejections` behavior do not have a catch handler to avoid infinite error loops: the recommendation is to **not use `async` functions as `'error'` event handlers**.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] All `EventEmitter`s emit the event `'newListener'` when new listeners are added and `'removeListener'` when existing listeners are removed.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] It supports the following option: `captureRejections` `<boolean>` It enables automatic capturing of promise rejection.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `EventEmitter` instance will emit its own `'newListener'` event *before* a listener is added to its internal array of listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Listeners registered for the `'newListener'` event are passed the event name and a reference to the listener being added.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `'removeListener'` event is emitted *after* the `listener` is removed.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Alias for `emitter.on(eventName, listener)`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Synchronously calls each of the listeners registered for the event named `eventName`, in the order they were registered, passing the supplied arguments to each.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns the current max listener value for the `EventEmitter` which is either set by `emitter.setMaxListeners(n)` or defaults to `events.defaultMaxListeners`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns the number of listeners listening for the event named `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] If `listener` is provided, it will return how many times the listener is found in the list of the listeners of the event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Adds the `listener` function to the end of the listeners array for the event named `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] No checks are made to see if the `listener` has already been added.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns a reference to the `EventEmitter`, so that calls can be chained.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] By default, event listeners are invoked in the order they are added.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Adds a **one-time** `listener` function for the event named `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Adds the `listener` function to the *beginning* of the listeners array for the event named `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Adds a **one-time** `listener` function for the event named `eventName` to the *beginning* of the listeners array.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Removes all listeners, or those of the specified `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] It is bad practice to remove listeners added elsewhere in the code, particularly when the `EventEmitter` instance was created by some other component or module (e.g. sockets or file streams).
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] `removeListener()` will remove, at most, one instance of a listener from the listener array.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] If any single listener has been added multiple times to the listener array for the specified `eventName`, then `removeListener()` must be called multiple times to remove each instance.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Once an event is emitted, all listeners attached to it at the time of emitting are called in order.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This implies that any `removeListener()` or `removeAllListeners()` calls *after* emitting and *before* the last listener finishes execution will not remove them from `emit()` in progress.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Because listeners are managed using an internal array, calling this will change the position indexes of any listener registered *after* the listener being removed.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This will not impact the order in which listeners are called, but it means that any copies of the listener array as returned by the `emitter.listeners()` method will need to be recreated.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] When a single function has been added as a handler multiple times for a single event (as in the example below), `removeListener()` will remove the most recently added instance.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] By default `EventEmitter`s will print a warning if more than `10` listeners are added for a particular event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This is a useful default that helps finding memory leaks.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `emitter.setMaxListeners()` method allows the limit to be modified for this specific `EventEmitter` instance.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The value can be set to `Infinity` (or `0`) to indicate an unlimited number of listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `Symbol.for('nodejs.rejection')` method is called in case a promise rejection happens when emitting an event and `captureRejections` is enabled on the emitter.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] By default, a maximum of `10` listeners can be registered for any single event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This limit can be changed for individual `EventEmitter` instances using the `emitter.setMaxListeners(n)` method.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] To change the default for *all* `EventEmitter` instances, the `events.defaultMaxListeners` property can be used.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] If this value is not a positive number, a `RangeError` is thrown.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Take caution when setting the `events.defaultMaxListeners` because the change affects *all* `EventEmitter` instances, including those created before the change is made.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] However, calling `emitter.setMaxListeners(n)` still has precedence over `events.defaultMaxListeners`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `EventEmitter` instance will allow more listeners to be added but will output a trace warning to stderr indicating that a "possible EventEmitter memory leak" has been detected.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] `defaultMaxListeners` has no effect on `AbortSignal` instances.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `--trace-warnings` command-line flag can be used to display the stack trace for such warnings.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The emitted warning can be inspected with `process.on('warning')` and will have the additional `emitter`, `type`, and `count` properties, referring to the event emitter instance, the event's name and the number of attached listeners, respectively.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Its `name` property is set to `'MaxListenersExceededWarning'`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This symbol shall be used to install a listener for only monitoring `'error'` events.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Listeners installed using this symbol are called before the regular `'error'` listeners are called.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Installing a listener using this symbol does not change the behavior once an `'error'` event is emitted.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Therefore, the process will still crash if no regular `'error'` listener is installed.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns a copy of the array of listeners for the event named `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For `EventEmitter`s this behaves exactly the same as calling `.listeners` on the emitter.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For `EventTarget`s this is the only way to get the event listeners for the event target.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns the currently set max amount of listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For `EventEmitter`s this behaves exactly the same as calling `.getMaxListeners` on the emitter.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For `EventTarget`s this is the only way to get the max event listeners for the event target.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Creates a `Promise` that is fulfilled when the `EventEmitter` emits the given event or that is rejected if the `EventEmitter` emits `'error'` while waiting.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `Promise` will resolve with an array of all the arguments emitted to the given event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The special handling of the `'error'` event is only used when `events.once()` is used to wait for another event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] It is important to be aware of execution order when using the `events.once()` method to await multiple events.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Conventional event listeners are called synchronously when the event is emitted.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] This guarantees that execution will not proceed beyond the emitted event until all listeners have finished executing.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The same is *not* true when awaiting Promises returned by `events.once()`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Promise tasks are not handled until after the current execution stack runs to completion, which means that multiple events could be emitted before asynchronous execution continues from the relevant `await` statement.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] As a result, events can be "missed" if a series of `await events.once()` statements is used to listen to multiple events, since there might be times where more than one event is emitted during the same phase of the event loop.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] To catch multiple events, create all of the Promises *before* awaiting any of them.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Change the default `captureRejections` option on all new `EventEmitter` objects.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] See how to write a custom rejection handler.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns the number of registered listeners for the event named `eventName`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For `EventEmitter`s this behaves exactly the same as calling `.listenerCount` on the emitter.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] For `EventTarget`s this is the only way to obtain the listener count.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] Returns an `AsyncIterator` that iterates `eventName` events.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] It will throw if the `EventEmitter` emits `'error'`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] It removes all listeners when exiting the loop.
[src:javascript/api-events-p01] The `value` returned by each iteration is an array composed of the emitted event arguments.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Listens once to the `abort` event on the provided `signal`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Listening to the `abort` event on abort signals is unsafe and may lead to resource leaks since another third party with the signal can call `e.stopImmediatePropagation()`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Unfortunately Node.js cannot change this since it would violate the web standard.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Additionally, the original API makes it easy to forget to remove listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] This API allows safely using `AbortSignal`s in Node.js APIs by solving these two issues by listening to the event such that `stopImmediatePropagation` does not prevent the listener from running.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Integrates `EventEmitter` with `<AsyncResource>` for `EventEmitter`s that require manual async tracking.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `EventEmitterAsyncResource` class has the same methods and takes the same options as `EventEmitter` and `AsyncResource` themselves.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The returned `AsyncResource` object has an additional `eventEmitter` property that provides a reference to this `EventEmitterAsyncResource`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] An error will be thrown if it is called more than once.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] If the resource is left to be collected by the GC then the `destroy` hooks will never be called.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] There are two key differences between the Node.js `EventTarget` and the `EventTarget` Web API: Whereas DOM `EventTarget` instances *may* be hierarchical, there is no concept of hierarchy and event propagation in Node.js.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] That is, an event dispatched to an `EventTarget` does not propagate through a hierarchy of nested target objects that may each have their own set of handlers for the event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] In the Node.js `EventTarget`, if an event listener is an async function or returns a `Promise`, and the returned `Promise` rejects, the rejection is automatically captured and handled the same way as a listener that throws synchronously (see `EventTarget` error handling for details).
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `NodeEventTarget` object implements a modified subset of the `EventEmitter` API that allows it to closely *emulate* an `EventEmitter` in certain situations.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] A `NodeEventTarget` is *not* an instance of `EventEmitter` and cannot be used in place of an `EventEmitter` in most cases.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Unlike `EventEmitter`, any given `listener` can be registered at most once per event `type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Attempts to register a `listener` multiple times are ignored.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `NodeEventTarget` does not emulate the full `EventEmitter` API.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Specifically the `prependListener()`, `prependOnceListener()`, `rawListeners()`, and `errorMonitor` APIs are not emulated.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `'newListener'` and `'removeListener'` events will also not be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `NodeEventTarget` does not implement any special default behavior for events with type `'error'`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `NodeEventTarget` supports `EventListener` objects as well as functions as handlers for all event types.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Event listeners registered for an event `type` may either be JavaScript functions or objects with a `handleEvent` property whose value is a function.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] In either case, the handler function is invoked with the `event` argument passed to the `eventTarget.dispatchEvent()` function.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Async functions may be used as event listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] If an async handler function rejects, the rejection is captured and handled as described in `EventTarget` error handling.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] An error thrown by one handler function does not prevent the other handlers from being invoked.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The return value of a handler function is ignored.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Handlers are always invoked in the order they were added.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] When a registered event listener throws (or returns a Promise that rejects), by default the error is treated as an uncaught exception on `process.nextTick()`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] This means uncaught exceptions in `EventTarget`s will terminate the Node.js process by default.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Throwing within an event listener will *not* stop the other registered handlers from being invoked.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `EventTarget` does not implement any special default handling for `'error'` type events like `EventEmitter`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Currently errors are first forwarded to the `process.on('error')` event before reaching `process.on('uncaughtException')`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] This behavior is deprecated and will change in a future release to align `EventTarget` with other Node.js APIs.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Any code relying on the `process.on('error')` event should be aligned with the new behavior.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `Event` object is an adaptation of the `Event` Web API.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Instances are created internally by Node.js.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] This is not used in Node.js and is provided purely for completeness.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Stability: 3 - Legacy: Use `event.stopPropagation()` instead.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Alias for `event.stopPropagation()` if set to `true`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Returns an array containing the current `EventTarget` as the only entry or empty if the event is not being dispatched.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Is `true` if `cancelable` is `true` and `event.preventDefault()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Stability: 3 - Legacy: The WHATWG spec considers it deprecated and users shouldn't use it at all.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Redundant with event constructors and incapable of setting `composed`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `<AbortSignal>` `"abort"` event is emitted with `isTrusted` set to `true`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The value is `false` in all other cases.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Sets the `defaultPrevented` property to `true` if `cancelable` is `true`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Stability: 3 - Legacy: Use `event.defaultPrevented` instead.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The value of `event.returnValue` is always the opposite of `event.defaultPrevented`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Stability: 3 - Legacy: Use `event.target` instead.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Stops the invocation of event listeners after the current one completes.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The millisecond timestamp when the `Event` object was created.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Adds a new handler for the `type` event.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Any given `listener` is added only once per `type` and per `capture` option value.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] If the `once` option is `true`, the `listener` is removed after the next time a `type` event is dispatched.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `capture` option is not used by Node.js in any functional way other than tracking registered event listeners per the `EventTarget` specification.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Specifically, the `capture` option is used as part of the key when registering a `listener`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Dispatches the `event` to the list of handlers for `event.type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The registered event listeners is synchronously invoked in the order they were registered.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Removes the `listener` from the list of handlers for event `type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `CustomEvent` object is an adaptation of the `CustomEvent` Web API.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The `NodeEventTarget` is a Node.js-specific extension to `EventTarget` that emulates a subset of the `EventEmitter` API.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that emulates the equivalent `EventEmitter` API.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The only difference between `addListener()` and `addEventListener()` is that `addListener()` will return a reference to the `EventTarget`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that dispatches the `arg` to the list of handlers for `type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that returns an array of event `type` names for which event listeners are registered.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that returns the number of event listeners registered for the `type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that sets the number of max event listeners as `n`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that returns the number of max event listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific alias for `eventTarget.removeEventListener()`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific alias for `eventTarget.addEventListener()`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that adds a `once` listener for the given event `type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] This is equivalent to calling `on` with the `once` option set to `true`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] If `type` is specified, removes all registered listeners for `type`, otherwise removes all registered listeners.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] Node.js-specific extension to the `EventTarget` class that removes the `listener` for the given `type`.
[src:javascript/api-events-p02] The only difference between `removeListener()` and `removeEventListener()` is that `removeListener()` will return a reference to the `EventTarget`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `node:fs` module enables interacting with the file system in a way modeled on standard POSIX functions.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] All file system operations have synchronous, callback, and promise-based forms, and are accessible using both CommonJS syntax and ES6 Modules (ESM).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback form takes a completion callback function as its last argument and invokes the operation asynchronously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The arguments passed to the completion callback depend on the method, but the first argument is always reserved for an exception.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback-based versions of the `node:fs` module APIs are preferable over the use of the promise APIs when maximal performance (both in terms of execution time and memory allocation) is required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The synchronous APIs block the Node.js event loop and further JavaScript execution until the operation is complete.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs/promises` API provides asynchronous file system methods that return promises.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The promise APIs use the underlying Node.js threadpool to perform file system operations off the event loop thread.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] These operations are not synchronized or threadsafe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Care must be taken when performing multiple concurrent modifications on the same file or data corruption may occur.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] A `<FileHandle>` object is an object wrapper for a numeric file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Instances of the `<FileHandle>` object are created by the `fsPromises.open()` method.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] All `<FileHandle>` objects are `<EventEmitter>`s.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If a `<FileHandle>` is not closed using the `filehandle.close()` method, it will try to automatically close the file descriptor and emit a process warning, helping to prevent memory leaks.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Please do not rely on this behavior because it can be unreliable and the file may not be closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Instead, always explicitly close `<FileHandle>`s.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Node.js may change this behavior in the future.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `'close'` event is emitted when the `<FileHandle>` has been closed and can no longer be used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When operating on file handles, the mode cannot be changed from what it was set to with `fsPromises.open()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Therefore, this is equivalent to `filehandle.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `options` can include `start` and `end` values to read a range of bytes from the file instead of the entire file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Both `start` and `end` are inclusive and start counting at 0, allowed values are in the [0, `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`] range.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `start` is omitted or `undefined`, `filehandle.createReadStream()` reads sequentially from the current file position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `encoding` can be any one of those accepted by `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the `FileHandle` points to a character device that only supports blocking reads (such as keyboard or sound card), read operations do not finish until data is available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This can prevent the process from exiting and the stream from closing naturally.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] By default, the stream will emit a `'close'` event after it has been destroyed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `autoClose` is false, then the file descriptor won't be closed, even if there's an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] It is the application's responsibility to close it and make sure there's no file descriptor leak.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `autoClose` is set to true (default behavior), on `'error'` or `'end'` the file descriptor will be closed automatically.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `options` may also include a `start` option to allow writing data at some position past the beginning of the file, allowed values are in the [0, `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`] range.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Modifying a file rather than replacing it may require the `flags` `open` option to be set to `r+` rather than the default `r`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `autoClose` is set to true (default behavior) on `'error'` or `'finish'` the file descriptor will be closed automatically.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Set the `emitClose` option to `false` to change this behavior.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Forces all currently queued I/O operations associated with the file to the operating system's synchronized I/O completion state.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Refer to the POSIX `fdatasync(2)` documentation for details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Unlike `filehandle.sync` this method does not flush modified metadata.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Return the file contents as an async iterable using the `node:stream/iter` pull model.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Reads are performed in `chunkSize`-byte chunks (default 128 KB).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If transforms are provided, they are applied via `stream/iter pull()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The file handle is locked while the iterable is being consumed and unlocked when iteration completes, an error occurs, or the consumer breaks.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Synchronous counterpart of `filehandle.pull()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns a sync iterable that reads the file using synchronous I/O on the main thread.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The file handle is locked while the iterable is being consumed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Unlike the async `pull()`, this method does not support `AbortSignal` since all operations are synchronous.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Reads data from the file and stores that in the given buffer.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file is not modified concurrently, the end-of-file is reached when the number of bytes read is zero.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns a byte-oriented `ReadableStream` that may be used to read the file's contents.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] While the `ReadableStream` will read the file to completion, it will not close the `FileHandle` automatically.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] User code must still call the `fileHandle.close()` method unless the `autoClose` option is set to `true`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously reads the entire contents of a file.
