[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The optional `options` argument can be an integer specifying `mode` (permission and sticky bits), or an object with a `mode` property and a `recursive` property indicating whether parent directories should be created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] A unique directory name is generated by appending six random characters to the end of the provided `prefix`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Due to platform inconsistencies, avoid trailing `X` characters in `prefix`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Some platforms, notably the BSDs, can return more than six random characters, and replace trailing `X` characters in `prefix` with random characters.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fsPromises.mkdtemp()` method will append the six randomly selected characters directly to the `prefix` string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For instance, given a directory `/tmp`, if the intention is to create a temporary directory *within* `/tmp`, the `prefix` must end with a trailing platform-specific path separator (`require('node:path').sep`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The resulting Promise holds an async-disposable object whose `path` property holds the created directory path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When the object is disposed, the directory and its contents will be removed asynchronously if it still exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the directory cannot be deleted, disposal will throw an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The object has an async `remove()` method which will perform the same task.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Both this function and the disposal function on the resulting object are async, so it should be used with `await` + `await using` as in `await using dir = await fsPromises.mkdtempDisposable('prefix')`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For detailed information, see the documentation of `fsPromises.mkdtemp()`.
