[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Do not use `fs.access()` to check for the accessibility of a file before calling `fs.open()`, `fs.readFile()`, or `fs.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The "not recommended" examples above check for accessibility and then use the file; the "recommended" examples are better because they use the file directly and handle the error, if any.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] In general, check for the accessibility of a file only if the file will not be used directly, for example when its accessibility is a signal from another process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Windows, access-control policies (ACLs) on a directory may limit access to a file or directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.access()` function, however, does not check the ACL and therefore may report that a path is accessible even if the ACL restricts the user from reading or writing to it.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `path` may be specified as a numeric file descriptor that has been opened for appending (using `fs.open()` or `fs.openSync()`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously changes the permissions of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] No arguments other than a possible exception are given to the completion callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] An easier method of constructing the `mode` is to use a sequence of three octal digits (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The left-most digit (`7` in the example), specifies the permissions for the file owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The middle digit (`6` in the example), specifies permissions for the group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The right-most digit (`5` in the example), specifies the permissions for others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example, the octal value `0o765` means: The owner may read, write, and execute the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When using raw numbers where file modes are expected, any value larger than `0o777` may result in platform-specific behaviors that are not supported to work consistently.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Therefore constants like `S_ISVTX`, `S_ISGID`, or `S_ISUID` are not exposed in `fs.constants`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Caveats: on Windows only the write permission can be changed, and the distinction among the permissions of group, owner, or others is not implemented.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously changes owner and group of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `chown(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Calling `fs.close()` on any file descriptor (`fd`) that is currently in use through any other `fs` operation may lead to undefined behavior.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `close(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] No arguments other than a possible exception are given to the callback function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Node.js makes no guarantees about the atomicity of the copy operation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If an error occurs after the destination file has been opened for writing, Node.js will attempt to remove the destination.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `mode` is an optional integer that specifies the behavior of the copy operation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] It is possible to create a mask consisting of the bitwise OR of two or more values (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_EXCL | fs.constants.COPYFILE_FICLONE`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_EXCL`: The copy operation will fail if `dest` already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_FICLONE`: The copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the platform does not support copy-on-write, then a fallback copy mechanism is used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.constants.COPYFILE_FICLONE_FORCE`: The copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the platform does not support copy-on-write, then the operation will fail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `fd` is specified and `start` is omitted or `undefined`, `fs.createReadStream()` reads sequentially from the current file position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `fd` is specified, `ReadStream` will ignore the `path` argument and will use the specified file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This means that no `'open'` event will be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fd` should be blocking; non-blocking `fd`s should be passed to `<net.Socket>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `fd` points to a character device that only supports blocking reads (such as keyboard or sound card), read operations do not finish until data is available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] By providing the `fs` option, it is possible to override the corresponding `fs` implementations for `open`, `read`, and `close`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When providing the `fs` option, an override for `read` is required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If no `fd` is provided, an override for `open` is also required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `mode` sets the file mode (permission and sticky bits), but only if the file was created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Modifying a file rather than replacing it may require the `flags` option to be set to `r+` rather than the default `w`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] By providing the `fs` option it is possible to override the corresponding `fs` implementations for `open`, `write`, `writev`, and `close`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Overriding `write()` without `writev()` can reduce performance as some optimizations (`_writev()`) will be disabled.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When providing the `fs` option, overrides for at least one of `write` and `writev` are required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If no `fd` option is supplied, an override for `open` is also required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `autoClose` is `true`, an override for `close` is also required.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Like `<fs.ReadStream>`, if `fd` is specified, `<fs.WriteStream>` will ignore the `path` argument and will use the specified file descriptor.
