[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the symbolic link referred to by the path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, stats)` where `stats` is a `<fs.Stats>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `lstat()` is identical to `stat()`, except that if `path` is a symbolic link, then the link itself is stat-ed, not the file that it refers to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `lstat(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback is given a possible exception and, if `recursive` is `true`, the first directory path created, `(err[, path])`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `path` can still be `undefined` when `recursive` is `true`, if no directory was created (for instance, if it was previously created).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Calling `fs.mkdir()` when `path` is a directory that exists results in an error only when `recursive` is false.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `mkdir(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Generates six random characters to be appended behind a required `prefix` to create a unique temporary directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The created directory path is passed as a string to the callback's second parameter.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.mkdtemp()` method will append the six randomly selected characters directly to the `prefix` string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `open(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Windows, only the write permission can be manipulated; see `fs.chmod()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, fd)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Functions based on `fs.open()` exhibit this behavior as well: `fs.writeFile()`, `fs.readFile()`, etc.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns a `<Blob>` whose data is backed by the given file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The file must not be modified after the `<Blob>` is created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Any modifications will cause reading the `<Blob>` data to fail with a `DOMException` error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `opendir(3)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Read data from the file specified by `fd`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback is given the three arguments, `(err, bytesRead, buffer)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If this method is invoked as its `util.promisify()`ed version, it returns a promise for an `Object` with `bytesRead` and `buffer` properties.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.read()` method reads data from the file specified by the file descriptor (`fd`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `length` argument indicates the maximum number of bytes that Node.js will attempt to read from the kernel.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] However, the actual number of bytes read (`bytesRead`) can be lower than the specified `length` for various reasons.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example: If the file is shorter than the specified `length`, `bytesRead` will be set to the actual number of bytes read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file encounters EOF (End of File) before the buffer could be filled, Node.js will read all available bytes until EOF is encountered, and the `bytesRead` parameter in the callback will indicate the actual number of bytes read, which may be less than the specified `length`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file is on a slow network `filesystem` or encounters any other issue during reading, `bytesRead` can be lower than the specified `length`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Therefore, when using `fs.read()`, it's important to check the `bytesRead` value to determine how many bytes were actually read from the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Depending on your application logic, you may need to handle cases where `bytesRead` is lower than the specified `length`, such as by wrapping the read call in a loop if you require a minimum amount of bytes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This behavior is similar to the POSIX `preadv2` function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Similar to the `fs.read()` function, this version takes an optional `options` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, files)` where `files` is an array of the names of the files in the directory excluding `'.'` and `'..'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `readdir(3)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the filenames passed to the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `options.withFileTypes` is set to `true`, the `files` array will contain `<fs.Dirent>` objects.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback is passed two arguments `(err, data)`, where `data` is the contents of the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If no encoding is specified, then the raw buffer is returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the supplied buffer is too small to contain the entire file, the callback is called with an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] When the path is a directory, the behavior of `fs.readFile()` and `fs.readFileSync()` is platform-specific.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On macOS, Linux, and Windows, an error will be returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] It is possible to abort an ongoing request using an `AbortSignal`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.readFile()` function buffers the entire file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] To minimize memory costs, when possible prefer streaming via `fs.createReadStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If a file descriptor is specified as the `path`, it will not be closed automatically.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The reading will begin at the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example, if the file already had `'Hello World'` and six bytes are read with the file descriptor, the call to `fs.readFile()` with the same file descriptor, would give `'World'`, rather than `'Hello World'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.readFile()` method asynchronously reads the contents of a file into memory one chunk at a time, allowing the event loop to turn between each chunk.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This allows the read operation to have less impact on other activity that may be using the underlying libuv thread pool but means that it will take longer to read a complete file into memory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The additional read overhead can vary broadly on different systems and depends on the type of file being read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the file type is not a regular file (a pipe for instance) and Node.js is unable to determine an actual file size, each read operation will load on 64 KiB of data.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For regular files, each read will process 512 KiB of data.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For applications that require as-fast-as-possible reading of file contents, it is better to use `fs.read()` directly and for application code to manage reading the full contents of the file itself.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The Node.js GitHub issue #25741 provides more information and a detailed analysis on the performance of `fs.readFile()` for multiple file sizes in different Node.js versions.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, linkString)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `readlink(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the link path passed to the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Read from a file specified by `fd` and write to an array of `ArrayBufferView`s using `readv()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `position` is the offset from the beginning of the file from where data should be read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `typeof position !== 'number'`, the data will be read from the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback will be given three arguments: `err`, `bytesRead`, and `buffers`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `bytesRead` is how many bytes were read from the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If this method is invoked as its `util.promisify()`ed version, it returns a promise for an `Object` with `bytesRead` and `buffers` properties.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously computes the canonical pathname by resolving `.`, `..`, and symbolic links.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] A canonical pathname is not necessarily unique.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Hard links and bind mounts can expose a file system entity through many pathnames.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This function behaves like `realpath(3)`, with some exceptions: No case conversion is performed on case-insensitive file systems.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The maximum number of symbolic links is platform-independent and generally (much) higher than what the native `realpath(3)` implementation supports.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `callback` gets two arguments `(err, resolvedPath)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] May use `process.cwd` to resolve relative paths.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the path passed to the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `path` resolves to a socket or a pipe, the function will return a system dependent name for that object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] A path that does not exist results in an ENOENT error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously rename file at `oldPath` to the pathname provided as `newPath`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] In the case that `newPath` already exists, it will be overwritten.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If there is a directory at `newPath`, an error will be raised instead.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Using `fs.rmdir()` on a file (not a directory) results in an `ENOENT` error on Windows and an `ENOTDIR` error on POSIX.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] To get a behavior similar to the `rm -rf` Unix command, use `fs.rm()` with options `{ recursive: true, force: true }`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously removes files and directories (modeled on the standard POSIX `rm` utility).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, stats)` where `stats` is an `<fs.Stats>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] In case of an error, the `err.code` will be one of Common System Errors.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Use `fs.lstat()` to look at the links themselves.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Using `fs.stat()` to check for the existence of a file before calling `fs.open()`, `fs.readFile()`, or `fs.writeFile()` is not recommended.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Instead, user code should open/read/write the file directly and handle the error raised if the file is not available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] To check if a file exists without manipulating it afterwards, `fs.access()` is recommended.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Returns information about the mounted file system which contains `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback gets two arguments `(err, stats)` where `stats` is an `<fs.StatFs>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Creates the link called `path` pointing to `target`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `symlink(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `type` argument is only available on Windows and ignored on other platforms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] A file descriptor can also be passed as the first argument.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Passing a file descriptor is deprecated and may result in an error being thrown in the future.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `truncate(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Asynchronously removes a file or symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.unlink()` will not work on a directory, empty or otherwise.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] To remove a directory, use `fs.rmdir()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] See the POSIX `unlink(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Stop watching for changes on `filename`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `listener` is specified, only that particular listener is removed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Otherwise, *all* listeners are removed, effectively stopping watching of `filename`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Calling `fs.unwatchFile()` with a filename that is not being watched is a no-op, not an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Using `fs.watch()` is more efficient than `fs.watchFile()` and `fs.unwatchFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `fs.watch()` should be used instead of `fs.watchFile()` and `fs.unwatchFile()` when possible.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `atime` and `mtime` arguments follow these rules: Values can be either numbers representing Unix epoch time in seconds, `Date`s, or a numeric string like `'123456789.0'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Watch for changes on `filename`, where `filename` is either a file or a directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If `options` is provided as a string, it specifies the `encoding`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Otherwise `options` should be passed as an object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The listener callback gets two arguments `(eventType, filename)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] `eventType` is either `'rename'` or `'change'`, and `filename` is the name of the file which triggered the event.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The listener callback is attached to the `'change'` event fired by `<fs.FSWatcher>`, but it is not the same thing as the `'change'` value of `eventType`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If a `signal` is passed, aborting the corresponding AbortController will close the returned `<fs.FSWatcher>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.watch` API is not 100% consistent across platforms, and is unavailable in some situations.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Windows, no events will be emitted if the watched directory is moved or renamed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] An `EPERM` error is reported when the watched directory is deleted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `fs.watch` API does not provide any protection with respect to malicious actions on the file system.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example, on Windows it is implemented by monitoring changes in a directory versus specific files.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This allows substitution of a file and fs reporting changes on the new file with the same filename.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] This feature depends on the underlying operating system providing a way to be notified of file system changes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Linux systems, this uses `inotify(7)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On macOS, this uses `kqueue(2)` for files and `FSEvents` for directories.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On SunOS systems (including Solaris and SmartOS), this uses `event ports`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Windows systems, this feature depends on `ReadDirectoryChangesW`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On AIX systems, this feature depends on `AHAFS`, which must be enabled.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On IBM i systems, this feature is not supported.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the underlying functionality is not available for some reason, then `fs.watch()` will not be able to function and may throw an exception.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] For example, watching files or directories can be unreliable, and in some cases impossible, on network file systems (NFS, SMB, etc) or host file systems when using virtualization software such as Vagrant or Docker.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] It is still possible to use `fs.watchFile()`, which uses stat polling, but this method is slower and less reliable.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] On Linux and macOS systems, `fs.watch()` resolves the path to an inode and watches the inode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] If the watched path is deleted and recreated, it is assigned a new inode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The watch will emit an event for the delete but will continue watching the *original* inode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Events for the new inode will not be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] AIX files retain the same inode for the lifetime of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Saving and closing a watched file on AIX will result in two notifications (one for adding new content, and one for truncation).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Providing `filename` argument in the callback is only supported on Linux, macOS, Windows, and AIX.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] Even on supported platforms, `filename` is not always guaranteed to be provided.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The callback `listener` will be called each time the file is accessed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `options` object may contain a boolean named `persistent` that indicates whether the process should continue to run as long as files are being watched.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p01] The `options` object may specify an `interval` property indicating how often the target should be polled in milliseconds.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] These stat objects are instances of `fs.Stat`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If the `bigint` option is `true`, the numeric values in these objects are specified as `BigInt`s.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] To be notified when the file was modified, not just accessed, it is necessary to compare `curr.mtimeMs` and `prev.mtimeMs`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When an `fs.watchFile` operation results in an `ENOENT` error, it will invoke the listener once, with all the fields zeroed (or, for dates, the Unix Epoch).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If the file is created later on, the listener will be called again, with the latest stat objects.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This is a change in functionality since v0.10.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Using `fs.watch()` is more efficient than `fs.watchFile` and `fs.unwatchFile`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `fs.watch` should be used instead of `fs.watchFile` and `fs.unwatchFile` when possible.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When a file being watched by `fs.watchFile()` disappears and reappears, then the contents of `previous` in the second callback event (the file's reappearance) will be the same as the contents of `previous` in the first callback event (its disappearance).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Write `buffer` to the file specified by `fd`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `offset` determines the part of the buffer to be written, and `length` is an integer specifying the number of bytes to write.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `position` refers to the offset from the beginning of the file where this data should be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `typeof position !== 'number'`, the data will be written at the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The callback will be given three arguments `(err, bytesWritten, buffer)` where `bytesWritten` specifies how many *bytes* were written from `buffer`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If this method is invoked as its `util.promisify()`ed version, it returns a promise for an `Object` with `bytesWritten` and `buffer` properties.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] It is unsafe to use `fs.write()` multiple times on the same file without waiting for the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For this scenario, `fs.createWriteStream()` is recommended.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Similar to the above `fs.write` function, this version takes an optional `options` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Write `string` to the file specified by `fd`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `string` is not a string, an exception is thrown.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `typeof position !== 'number'` the data will be written at the current position.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `encoding` is the expected string encoding.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The callback will receive the arguments `(err, written, string)` where `written` specifies how many *bytes* the passed string required to be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Bytes written is not necessarily the same as string characters written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] On Windows, if the file descriptor is connected to the console (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `fd == 1` or `stdout`) a string containing non-ASCII characters will not be rendered properly by default, regardless of the encoding used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] It is possible to configure the console to render UTF-8 properly by changing the active codepage with the `chcp 65001` command.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When `file` is a filename, asynchronously writes data to the file, replacing the file if it already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When `file` is a file descriptor, the behavior is similar to calling `fs.write()` directly (which is recommended).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See the notes below on using a file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] It is unsafe to use `fs.writeFile()` multiple times on the same file without waiting for the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Similarly to `fs.readFile` - `fs.writeFile` is a convenience method that performs multiple `write` calls internally to write the buffer passed to it.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For performance sensitive code consider using `fs.createWriteStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] It is possible to use an `<AbortSignal>` to cancel an `fs.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The difference from directly calling `fs.write()` is that under some unusual conditions, `fs.write()` might write only part of the buffer and need to be retried to write the remaining data, whereas `fs.writeFile()` retries until the data is entirely written (or an error occurs).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The implications of this are a common source of confusion.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] In the file descriptor case, the file is not replaced!
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The data is not necessarily written to the beginning of the file, and the file's original data may remain before and/or after the newly written data.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If a file name had been used instead of a descriptor, the file would be guaranteed to contain only `', World'`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Write an array of `ArrayBufferView`s to the file specified by `fd` using `writev()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `position` is the offset from the beginning of the file where this data should be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The callback will be given three arguments: `err`, `bytesWritten`, and `buffers`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `bytesWritten` is how many bytes were written from `buffers`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If this method is `util.promisify()`ed, it returns a promise for an `Object` with `bytesWritten` and `buffers` properties.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] It is unsafe to use `fs.writev()` multiple times on the same file without waiting for the callback.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For this scenario, use `fs.createWriteStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The synchronous APIs perform all operations synchronously, blocking the event loop until the operation completes or fails.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously tests a user's permissions for the file or directory specified by `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If any of the accessibility checks fail, an `Error` will be thrown.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously append data to a file, creating the file if it does not yet exist.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.chmod()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See the POSIX `chmod(2)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously changes owner and group of a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This is the synchronous version of `fs.chown()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calling `fs.closeSync()` on any file descriptor (`fd`) that is currently in use through any other `fs` operation may lead to undefined behavior.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously copies the entire directory structure from `src` to `dest`, including subdirectories and files.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the path exists, `false` otherwise.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.exists()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] `fs.exists()` is deprecated, but `fs.existsSync()` is not.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The `callback` parameter to `fs.exists()` accepts parameters that are inconsistent with other Node.js callbacks.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.ftruncate()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See the POSIX `lchown(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Change the file system timestamps of the symbolic link referenced by `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`, or throws an exception when parameters are incorrect or the operation fails.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This is the synchronous version of `fs.lutimes()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the symbolic link referred to by `path`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `undefined`, or if `recursive` is `true`, the first directory path created.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] This is the synchronous version of `fs.mkdir()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.mkdtemp()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns a disposable object whose `path` property holds the created directory path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] When the object is disposed, the directory and its contents will be removed if it still exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The object has a `remove()` method which will perform the same task.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of `fs.mkdtemp()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] There is no callback-based version of this API because it is designed for use with the `using` syntax.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns an integer representing the file descriptor.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.open()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the filenames returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If `options.withFileTypes` is set to `true`, the result will contain `<fs.Dirent>` objects.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.readFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If the `encoding` option is specified then this function returns a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If the supplied buffer is too small to contain the entire file, an error will be thrown.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns the symbolic link's string value.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.read()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Similar to the above `fs.readSync` function, this version takes an optional `options` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.readv()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.realpath()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The optional `options` argument can be a string specifying an encoding, or an object with an `encoding` property specifying the character encoding to use for the path returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Renames the file from `oldPath` to `newPath`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See the POSIX `rename(2)` documentation for more details.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Using `fs.rmdirSync()` on a file (not a directory) results in an `ENOENT` error on Windows and an `ENOTDIR` error on POSIX.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] To get a behavior similar to the `rm -rf` Unix command, use `fs.rmSync()` with options `{ recursive: true, force: true }`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously removes files and directories (modeled on the standard POSIX `rm` utility).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Retrieves the `<fs.Stats>` for the path.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.symlink()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] In this case, `fs.ftruncateSync()` is called.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.utimes()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.writeFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.write(fd, buffer...)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.write(fd, string...)`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] For detailed information, see the documentation of the asynchronous version of this API: `fs.writev()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The common objects are shared by all of the file system API variants (promise, callback, and synchronous).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A class representing a directory stream.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Asynchronously close the directory's underlying resource handle.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A promise is returned that will be fulfilled after the resource has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The `callback` will be called after the resource handle has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously close the directory's underlying resource handle.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The read-only path of this directory as was provided to `fs.opendir()`, `fs.opendirSync()`, or `fsPromises.opendir()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Asynchronously read the next directory entry via `readdir(3)` as an `<fs.Dirent>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A promise is returned that will be fulfilled with an `<fs.Dirent>`, or `null` if there are no more directory entries to read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Directory entries returned by this function are in no particular order as provided by the operating system's underlying directory mechanisms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Entries added or removed while iterating over the directory might not be included in the iteration results.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] After the read is completed, the `callback` will be called with an `<fs.Dirent>`, or `null` if there are no more directory entries to read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Synchronously read the next directory entry as an `<fs.Dirent>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] See the POSIX `readdir(3)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] If there are no more directory entries to read, `null` will be returned.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Asynchronously iterates over the directory until all entries have been read.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Refer to the POSIX `readdir(3)` documentation for more detail.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Entries returned by the async iterator are always an `<fs.Dirent>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The `null` case from `dir.read()` is handled internally.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Directory entries returned by this iterator are in no particular order as provided by the operating system's underlying directory mechanisms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calls `dir.close()` if the directory handle is open, and returns a promise that fulfills when disposal is complete.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Calls `dir.closeSync()` if the directory handle is open, and returns `undefined`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] A representation of a directory entry, which can be a file or a subdirectory within the directory, as returned by reading from an `<fs.Dir>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] The directory entry is a combination of the file name and file type pairs.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Additionally, when `fs.readdir()` or `fs.readdirSync()` is called with the `withFileTypes` option set to `true`, the resulting array is filled with `<fs.Dirent>` objects, rather than strings or `<Buffer>`s.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a block device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p02] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a character device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a file system directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a first-in-first-out (FIFO) pipe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a regular file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a socket.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Dirent>` object describes a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The file name that this `<fs.Dirent>` object refers to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The type of this value is determined by the `options.encoding` passed to `fs.readdir()` or `fs.readdirSync()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The path to the parent directory of the file this `<fs.Dirent>` object refers to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A successful call to `fs.watch()` method will return a new `<fs.FSWatcher>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] All `<fs.FSWatcher>` objects emit a `'change'` event whenever a specific watched file is modified.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when something changes in a watched directory or file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `filename` argument may not be provided depending on operating system support.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the watcher stops watching for changes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The closed `<fs.FSWatcher>` object is no longer usable in the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when an error occurs while watching the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The errored `<fs.FSWatcher>` object is no longer usable in the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Stop watching for changes on the given `<fs.FSWatcher>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Once stopped, the `<fs.FSWatcher>` object is no longer usable.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When called, requests that the Node.js event loop *not* exit so long as the `<fs.FSWatcher>` is active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Calling `watcher.ref()` multiple times will have no effect.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] By default, all `<fs.FSWatcher>` objects are "ref'ed", making it normally unnecessary to call `watcher.ref()` unless `watcher.unref()` had been called previously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When called, the active `<fs.FSWatcher>` object will not require the Node.js event loop to remain active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If there is no other activity keeping the event loop running, the process may exit before the `<fs.FSWatcher>` object's callback is invoked.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Calling `watcher.unref()` multiple times will have no effect.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A successful call to `fs.watchFile()` method will return a new `<fs.StatWatcher>` object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When called, requests that the Node.js event loop *not* exit so long as the `<fs.StatWatcher>` is active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] By default, all `<fs.StatWatcher>` objects are "ref'ed", making it normally unnecessary to call `watcher.ref()` unless `watcher.unref()` had been called previously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When called, the active `<fs.StatWatcher>` object will not require the Node.js event loop to remain active.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If there is no other activity keeping the event loop running, the process may exit before the `<fs.StatWatcher>` object's callback is invoked.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Instances of `<fs.ReadStream>` cannot be constructed directly.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] They are created and returned using the `fs.createReadStream()` function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.ReadStream>`'s underlying file descriptor has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.ReadStream>`'s file descriptor has been opened.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.ReadStream>` is ready to be used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of bytes that have been read so far.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The path to the file the stream is reading from as specified in the first argument to `fs.createReadStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `path` is passed as a string, then `readStream.path` will be a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `path` is passed as a `<Buffer>`, then `readStream.path` will be a `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `fd` is specified, then `readStream.path` will be `undefined`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This property is `true` if the underlying file has not been opened yet, i.e. before the `'ready'` event is emitted.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A `<fs.Stats>` object provides information about a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Objects returned from `fs.stat()`, `fs.lstat()`, `fs.fstat()`, and their synchronous counterparts are of this type.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `bigint` in the `options` passed to those methods is true, the numeric values will be `bigint` instead of `number`, and the object will contain additional nanosecond-precision properties suffixed with `Ns`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a block device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a character device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a file system directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the `<fs.Stats>` object was obtained from calling `fs.lstat()` on a symbolic link which resolves to a directory, this method will return `false`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This is because `fs.lstat()` returns information about a symbolic link itself and not the path it resolves to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a first-in-first-out (FIFO) pipe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a regular file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a socket.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Returns `true` if the `<fs.Stats>` object describes a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This method is only valid when using `fs.lstat()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The numeric identifier of the device containing the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The file system specific "Inode" number for the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A bit-field describing the file type and mode.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of hard-links that exist for the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The numeric user identifier of the user that owns the file (POSIX).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The numeric group identifier of the group that owns the file (POSIX).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A numeric device identifier if the file represents a device.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the underlying file system does not support getting the size of the file, this will be `0`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The file system block size for i/o operations.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of blocks allocated for this file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was accessed expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was modified expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time the file status was changed expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the creation time of this file expressed in milliseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Only present when `bigint: true` is passed into the method that generates the object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was accessed expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was modified expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time the file status was changed expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the creation time of this file expressed in nanoseconds since the POSIX Epoch.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was accessed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time this file was modified.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the last time the file status was changed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The timestamp indicating the creation time of this file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `atimeMs`, `mtimeMs`, `ctimeMs`, `birthtimeMs` properties are numeric values that hold the corresponding times in milliseconds.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When `bigint: true` is passed into the method that generates the object, the properties will be bigints, otherwise they will be numbers.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `atimeNs`, `mtimeNs`, `ctimeNs`, `birthtimeNs` properties are bigints that hold the corresponding times in nanoseconds.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] They are only present when `bigint: true` is passed into the method that generates the object.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `atime`, `mtime`, `ctime`, and `birthtime` are `Date` object alternate representations of the various times.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `Date` and number values are not connected.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Assigning a new number value, or mutating the `Date` value, will not be reflected in the corresponding alternate representation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The times in the stat object have the following semantics: `atime` "Access Time": Time when file data last accessed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Changed by the `mknod(2)`, `utimes(2)`, and `read(2)` system calls.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `mtime` "Modified Time": Time when file data last modified.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Changed by the `mknod(2)`, `utimes(2)`, and `write(2)` system calls.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `ctime` "Change Time": Time when file status was last changed (inode data modification).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `birthtime` "Birth Time": Time of file creation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On file systems where birthtime is not available, this field may instead hold either the `ctime` or `1970-01-01T00:00Z` (ie, Unix epoch timestamp `0`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This value may be greater than `atime` or `mtime` in this case.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Darwin and other FreeBSD variants, also set if the `atime` is explicitly set to an earlier value than the current `birthtime` using the `utimes(2)` system call.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Prior to Node.js 0.12, the `ctime` held the `birthtime` on Windows systems.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] As of 0.12, `ctime` is not "creation time", and on Unix systems, it never was.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Provides information about a mounted file system.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Objects returned from `fs.statfs()` and its synchronous counterpart are of this type.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Free blocks available to unprivileged users.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] A platform-specific numeric identifier for the type of file system.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This value corresponds to the `f_type` field returned by `statfs(2)` on POSIX systems (for example, `0xEF53` for ext4 on Linux).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Its meaning is OS-dependent and is not guaranteed to be consistent across platforms.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] An optimized UTF-8 stream writer that allows for flushing all the internal buffering on demand.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] It handles `EAGAIN` errors correctly, allowing for customization, for example, by dropping content if the disk is busy.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'close'` event is emitted when the stream is fully closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'drain'` event is emitted when the internal buffer has drained sufficiently to allow continued writing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'drop'` event is emitted when the maximal length is reached and that data will not be written.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The data that was dropped is passed as the first argument to the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'error'` event is emitted when an error occurs.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'finish'` event is emitted when the stream has been ended and all data has been flushed to the underlying file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'ready'` event is emitted when the stream is ready to accept writes.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The `'write'` event is emitted when a write operation has completed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The number of bytes written is passed as the first argument to the event handler.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Close the stream immediately, without flushing the internal buffer.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Close the stream gracefully, flushing the internal buffer before closing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Writes the current buffer to the file if a write was not in progress.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Do nothing if `minLength` is zero or if it is already writing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Flushes the buffered data synchronously.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Reopen the file in place, useful for log rotation.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] When the `options.contentMode` is set to `'utf8'` when the stream is created, the `data` argument must be a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the `contentMode` is set to `'buffer'`, the `data` argument must be a `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Instances of `<fs.WriteStream>` cannot be constructed directly.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] They are created and returned using the `fs.createWriteStream()` function.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.WriteStream>`'s underlying file descriptor has been closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.WriteStream>`'s file is opened.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Emitted when the `<fs.WriteStream>` is ready to be used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Does not include data that is still queued for writing.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Optionally accepts a callback that will be executed once the `writeStream` is closed.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The path to the file the stream is writing to as specified in the first argument to `fs.createWriteStream()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `path` is passed as a string, then `writeStream.path` will be a string.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If `path` is passed as a `<Buffer>`, then `writeStream.path` will be a `<Buffer>`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are exported by `fs.constants` and `fsPromises.constants`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Not every constant will be available on every operating system; this is especially important for Windows, where many of the POSIX specific definitions are not available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] For portable applications it is recommended to check for their presence before use.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] To use more than one constant, use the bitwise OR `|` operator.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use as the `mode` parameter passed to `fsPromises.access()`, `fs.access()`, and `fs.accessSync()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `F_OK` Flag indicating that the file is visible to the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This is useful for determining if a file exists, but says nothing about `rwx` permissions.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `R_OK` Flag indicating that the file can be read by the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `W_OK` Flag indicating that the file can be written by the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `X_OK` Flag indicating that the file can be executed by the calling process.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This has no effect on Windows (will behave like `fs.constants.F_OK`).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The definitions are also available on Windows.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with `fs.copyFile()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `COPYFILE_EXCL` If present, the copy operation will fail with an error if the destination path already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `COPYFILE_FICLONE` If present, the copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the underlying platform does not support copy-on-write, then a fallback copy mechanism is used.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `COPYFILE_FICLONE_FORCE` If present, the copy operation will attempt to create a copy-on-write reflink.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] If the underlying platform does not support copy-on-write, then the operation will fail with an error.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with `fs.open()`.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `O_RDONLY` Flag indicating to open a file for read-only access.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_WRONLY` Flag indicating to open a file for write-only access.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_RDWR` Flag indicating to open a file for read-write access.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_CREAT` Flag indicating to create the file if it does not already exist.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_EXCL` Flag indicating that opening a file should fail if the `O_CREAT` flag is set and the file already exists.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NOCTTY` Flag indicating that if path identifies a terminal device, opening the path shall not cause that terminal to become the controlling terminal for the process (if the process does not already have one).
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_TRUNC` Flag indicating that if the file exists and is a regular file, and the file is opened successfully for write access, its length shall be truncated to zero.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_APPEND` Flag indicating that data will be appended to the end of the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_DIRECTORY` Flag indicating that the open should fail if the path is not a directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NOATIME` Flag indicating reading accesses to the file system will no longer result in an update to the `atime` information associated with the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This flag is available on Linux operating systems only.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NOFOLLOW` Flag indicating that the open should fail if the path is a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_SYNC` Flag indicating that the file is opened for synchronized I/O with write operations waiting for file integrity.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_DSYNC` Flag indicating that the file is opened for synchronized I/O with write operations waiting for data integrity.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_SYMLINK` Flag indicating to open the symbolic link itself rather than the resource it is pointing to.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_DIRECT` When set, an attempt will be made to minimize caching effects of file I/O.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `O_NONBLOCK` Flag indicating to open the file in nonblocking mode when possible.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `UV_FS_O_FILEMAP` When set, a memory file mapping is used to access the file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] This flag is available on Windows operating systems only.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On other operating systems, this flag is ignored.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Windows, only `O_APPEND`, `O_CREAT`, `O_EXCL`, `O_RDONLY`, `O_RDWR`, `O_TRUNC`, `O_WRONLY`, and `UV_FS_O_FILEMAP` are available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with the `<fs.Stats>` object's `mode` property for determining a file's type.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `S_IFMT` Bit mask used to extract the file type code.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFREG` File type constant for a regular file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFDIR` File type constant for a directory.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFCHR` File type constant for a character-oriented device file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFBLK` File type constant for a block-oriented device file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFIFO` File type constant for a FIFO/pipe.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFLNK` File type constant for a symbolic link.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IFSOCK` File type constant for a socket.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Windows, only `S_IFCHR`, `S_IFDIR`, `S_IFLNK`, `S_IFMT`, and `S_IFREG`, are available.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] The following constants are meant for use with the `<fs.Stats>` object's `mode` property for determining the access permissions for a file.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] Constant Description `S_IRWXU` File mode indicating readable, writable, and executable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRUSR` File mode indicating readable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IWUSR` File mode indicating writable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IXUSR` File mode indicating executable by owner.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRWXG` File mode indicating readable, writable, and executable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRGRP` File mode indicating readable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IWGRP` File mode indicating writable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IXGRP` File mode indicating executable by group.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IRWXO` File mode indicating readable, writable, and executable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IROTH` File mode indicating readable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IWOTH` File mode indicating writable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] `S_IXOTH` File mode indicating executable by others.
[src:javascript/api-fs-p03] On Windows, only `S_IRUSR` and `S_IWUSR` are available.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This module, containing both a client and server, can be imported via `require('node:http')` (CommonJS) or `import * as http from 'node:http'` (ES module).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The HTTP interfaces in Node.js are designed to support many features of the protocol which have been traditionally difficult to use.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In particular, large, possibly chunk-encoded, messages.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The interface is careful to never buffer entire requests or responses, so the user is able to stream data.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In order to support the full spectrum of possible HTTP applications, the Node.js HTTP API is very low-level.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It deals with stream handling and message parsing only.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It parses a message into headers and body but it does not parse the actual headers or the body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] See `message.headers` for details on how duplicate headers are handled.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The raw headers as they were received are retained in the `rawHeaders` property, which is an array of `[key, value, key2, value2, ...]`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An `Agent` is responsible for managing connection persistence and reuse for HTTP clients.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It maintains a queue of pending requests for a given host and port, reusing a single socket connection for each until the queue is empty, at which time the socket is either destroyed or put into a pool where it is kept to be used again for requests to the same host and port.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Whether it is destroyed or pooled depends on the `keepAlive` option.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Pooled connections have TCP Keep-Alive enabled for them, but servers may still close idle connections, in which case they will be removed from the pool and a new connection will be made when a new HTTP request is made for that host and port.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Servers may also refuse to allow multiple requests over the same connection, in which case the connection will have to be remade for every request and cannot be pooled.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `Agent` will still make the requests to that server, but each one will occur over a new connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When a connection is closed by the client or the server, it is removed from the pool.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Any unused sockets in the pool will be unrefed so as not to keep the Node.js process running when there are no outstanding requests.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It is good practice, to `destroy()` an `Agent` instance when it is no longer in use, because unused sockets consume OS resources.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sockets are removed from an agent when the socket emits either a `'close'` event or an `'agentRemove'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An agent may also be used for an individual request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] By providing `{agent: false}` as an option to the `http.get()` or `http.request()` functions, a one-time use `Agent` with default options will be used for the client connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `options` in `socket.connect()` are also supported.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Produces a socket/stream to be used for HTTP requests.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] By default, this function behaves identically to `net.createConnection()`, synchronously returning the created socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The optional `callback` parameter in the signature is **not** used by this default implementation.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, custom agents may override this method to provide greater flexibility, for example, to create sockets asynchronously.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When overriding `createConnection`: **Synchronous socket creation**: The overriding method can return the socket/stream directly.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] **Asynchronous socket creation**: The overriding method can accept the `callback` and pass the created socket/stream to it (e.g., `callback(null, newSocket)`).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If an error occurs during socket creation, it should be passed as the first argument to the `callback` (e.g., `callback(err)`).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The agent will call the provided `createConnection` function with `options` and this internal `callback`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `callback` provided by the agent has a signature of `(err, stream)`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Called when `socket` is detached from a request and could be persisted by the `Agent`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method can be overridden by a particular `Agent` subclass.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this method returns a falsy value, the socket will be destroyed instead of persisting it for use with the next request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `socket` argument can be an instance of `<net.Socket>`, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Called when `socket` is attached to `request` after being persisted because of the keep-alive options.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Destroy any sockets that are currently in use by the agent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, if using an agent with `keepAlive` enabled, then it is best to explicitly shut down the agent when it is no longer needed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Otherwise, sockets might stay open for quite a long time before the server terminates them.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An object which contains arrays of sockets currently awaiting use by the agent when `keepAlive` is enabled.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sockets in the `freeSockets` list will be automatically destroyed and removed from the array on `'timeout'`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Get a unique name for a set of request options, to determine whether a connection can be reused.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For an HTTP agent, this returns `host:port:localAddress` or `host:port:localAddress:family`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For an HTTPS agent, the name includes the CA, cert, ciphers, and other HTTPS/TLS-specific options that determine socket reusability.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For agents with `keepAlive` enabled, this sets the maximum number of sockets that will be left open in the free state.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Determines how many concurrent sockets the agent can have open per origin.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Origin is the returned value of `agent.getName()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Determines how many concurrent sockets the agent can have open.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Unlike `maxSockets`, this parameter applies across all origins.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An object which contains queues of requests that have not yet been assigned to sockets.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An object which contains arrays of sockets currently in use by the agent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This object is created internally and returned from `http.request()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It represents an *in-progress* request whose header has already been queued.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The header is still mutable using the `setHeader(name, value)`, `getHeader(name)`, `removeHeader(name)` API.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The actual header will be sent along with the first data chunk or when calling `request.end()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] To get the response, add a listener for `'response'` to the request object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `'response'` will be emitted from the request object when the response headers have been received.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `'response'` event is executed with one argument which is an instance of `http.IncomingMessage`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] During the `'response'` event, one can add listeners to the response object; particularly to listen for the `'data'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If no `'response'` handler is added, then the response will be entirely discarded.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, if a `'response'` event handler is added, then the data from the response object **must** be consumed, either by calling `response.read()` whenever there is a `'readable'` event, or by adding a `'data'` handler, or by calling the `.resume()` method.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Until the data is consumed, the `'end'` event will not fire.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Also, until the data is read it will consume memory that can eventually lead to a 'process out of memory' error.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For backward compatibility, `res` will only emit `'error'` if there is an `'error'` listener registered.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Set `Content-Length` header to limit the response body size.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `response.strictContentLength` is set to `true`, mismatching the `Content-Length` header value will result in an `Error` being thrown, identified by `code:` `'ERR_HTTP_CONTENT_LENGTH_MISMATCH'`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `Content-Length` value should be in bytes, not characters.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Use `Buffer.byteLength()` to determine the length of the body in bytes.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the request has been aborted by the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event is only emitted on the first call to `abort()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Indicates that the request is completed, or its underlying connection was terminated prematurely (before the response completion).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a server responds to a request with a `CONNECT` method.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not being listened for, clients receiving a `CONNECT` method will have their connections closed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event is guaranteed to be passed an instance of the `<net.Socket>` class, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`, unless the user specifies a socket type other than `<net.Socket>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the server sends a '100 Continue' HTTP response, usually because the request contained 'Expect: 100-continue'.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This is an instruction that the client should send the request body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] More specifically, this event is emitted when the last segment of the request headers and body have been handed off to the operating system for transmission over the network.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It does not imply that the server has received anything yet.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the server sends a 1xx intermediate response (excluding 101 Upgrade).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] 101 Upgrade statuses do not fire this event due to their break from the traditional HTTP request/response chain, such as web sockets, in-place TLS upgrades, or HTTP 2.0.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] To be notified of 101 Upgrade notices, listen for the `'upgrade'` event instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when a response is received to this request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the underlying socket times out from inactivity.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This only notifies that the socket has been idle.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a server responds to a request with an upgrade.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not being listened for and the response status code is 101 Switching Protocols, clients receiving an upgrade header will have their connections closed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Stability: 0 - Deprecated: Use `request.destroy()` instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calling this will cause remaining data in the response to be dropped and the socket to be destroyed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `request.aborted` property will be `true` if the request has been aborted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If any parts of the body are unsent, it will flush them to the stream.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If the request is chunked, this will send the terminating `'0\r\n\r\n'`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `data` is specified, it is equivalent to calling `request.write(data, encoding)` followed by `request.end(callback)`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `callback` is specified, it will be called when the request stream is finished.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Optionally emit an `'error'` event, and emit a `'close'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calling this will cause remaining data in the response to be dropped, and the socket to be destroyed if used, or returned to the corresponding Agent pool otherwise if possible.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] See `writable.destroy()` for further details.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Is `true` after `request.destroy()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] See `writable.destroyed` for further details.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `request.finished` property will be `true` if `request.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `request.end()` will automatically be called if the request was initiated via `http.get()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For efficiency reasons, Node.js normally buffers the request headers until `request.end()` is called or the first chunk of request data is written.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It then tries to pack the request headers and data into a single TCP packet.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] That's usually desired (it saves a TCP round-trip), but not when the first data is not sent until possibly much later.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `request.flushHeaders()` bypasses the optimization and kickstarts the request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns an array containing the unique names of the current outgoing headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns a shallow copy of the current outgoing headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Since a shallow copy is used, array values may be mutated without additional calls to various header-related http module methods.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The keys of the returned object are the header names and the values are the respective header values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The object returned by the `request.getHeaders()` method *does not* prototypically inherit from the JavaScript `Object`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns an array containing the unique names of the current outgoing raw headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns `true` if the header identified by `name` is currently set in the outgoing headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When sending request through a keep-alive enabled agent, the underlying socket might be reused.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sets a single header value for headers object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this header already exists in the to-be-sent headers, its value will be replaced.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Use an array of strings here to send multiple headers with the same name.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Non-string values will be stored without modification.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Therefore, `request.getHeader()` may return non-string values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When the value is a string an exception will be thrown if it contains characters outside the `latin1` encoding.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Once a socket is assigned to this request and is connected `socket.setNoDelay()` will be called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Once a socket is assigned to this request and is connected `socket.setKeepAlive()` will be called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Once a socket is assigned to this request and is connected `socket.setTimeout()` will be called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Usually users will not want to access this property.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This property is guaranteed to be an instance of the `<net.Socket>` class, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`, unless the user specified a socket type other than `<net.Socket>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Is `true` after `request.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This property does not indicate whether the data has been flushed, for this use `request.writableFinished` instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Is `true` if all data has been flushed to the underlying system, immediately before the `'finish'` event is emitted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method can be called multiple times.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If no `Content-Length` is set, data will automatically be encoded in HTTP Chunked transfer encoding, so that server knows when the data ends.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` header is added.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calling `request.end()` is necessary to finish sending the request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `encoding` argument is optional and only applies when `chunk` is a string.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `callback` argument is optional and will be called when this chunk of data is flushed, but only if the chunk is non-empty.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns `true` if the entire data was flushed successfully to the kernel buffer.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Returns `false` if all or part of the data was queued in user memory.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `'drain'` will be emitted when the buffer is free again.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When `write` function is called with empty string or buffer, it does nothing and waits for more input.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a request with an HTTP `Expect: 100-continue` is received.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not listened for, the server will automatically respond with a `100 Continue` as appropriate.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Handling this event involves calling `response.writeContinue()` if the client should continue to send the request body, or generating an appropriate HTTP response (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] 400 Bad Request) if the client should not continue to send the request body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When this event is emitted and handled, the `'request'` event will not be emitted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a request with an HTTP `Expect` header is received, where the value is not `100-continue`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not listened for, the server will automatically respond with a `417 Expectation Failed` as appropriate.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If a client connection emits an `'error'` event, it will be forwarded here.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Listener of this event is responsible for closing/destroying the underlying socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] For example, one may wish to more gracefully close the socket with a custom HTTP response instead of abruptly severing the connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The socket **must be closed or destroyed** before the listener ends.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Default behavior is to try close the socket with an HTTP '400 Bad Request', or an HTTP '431 Request Header Fields Too Large' in the case of an `HPE_HEADER_OVERFLOW` error.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If the socket is not writable or headers of the current attached `http.ServerResponse` has been sent, it is immediately destroyed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When the `'clientError'` event occurs, there is no `request` or `response` object, so any HTTP response sent, including response headers and payload, *must* be written directly to the `socket` object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Care must be taken to ensure the response is a properly formatted HTTP response message.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `err` is an instance of `Error` with two extra columns: `bytesParsed`: the bytes count of request packet that Node.js may have parsed correctly; `rawPacket`: the raw packet of current request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In some cases, the client has already received the response and/or the socket has already been destroyed, like in case of `ECONNRESET` errors.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a client requests an HTTP `CONNECT` method.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If this event is not listened for, then clients requesting a `CONNECT` method will have their connections closed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] After this event is emitted, the request's socket will not have a `'data'` event listener, meaning it will need to be bound in order to handle data sent to the server on that socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event is emitted when a new TCP stream is established.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] `socket` is typically an object of type `net.Socket`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Usually users will not want to access this event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In particular, the socket will not emit `'readable'` events because of how the protocol parser attaches to the socket.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `socket` can also be accessed at `request.socket`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This event can also be explicitly emitted by users to inject connections into the HTTP server.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In that case, any `Duplex` stream can be passed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `socket.setTimeout()` is called here, the timeout will be replaced with `server.keepAliveTimeout` when the socket has served a request (if `server.keepAliveTimeout` is non-zero).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When the number of requests on a socket reaches the threshold of `server.maxRequestsPerSocket`, the server will drop new requests and emit `'dropRequest'` event instead, then send `503` to client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] There may be multiple requests per connection (in the case of HTTP Keep-Alive connections).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted each time a client's HTTP upgrade request is accepted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] You can control this more precisely by using the server `shouldUpgradeCallback` option.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Listening to this event is optional and clients cannot insist on a protocol change.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If an upgrade is accepted by `shouldUpgradeCallback` but no event handler is registered then the socket will be destroyed, resulting in an immediate connection closure for the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] In the uncommon case that the incoming request has a body, this body will be parsed as normal, separate to the upgrade stream, and the raw stream data will only begin after it has completed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] To ensure that reading from the stream isn't blocked by waiting for the request body to be read, any reads on the stream will start the request body flowing automatically.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If you want to read the request body, ensure that you do so (i.e. you attach `'data'` listeners) before starting to read from the upgraded stream.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The stream argument will typically be the `<net.Socket>` instance used by the request, but in some cases (such as with a request body) it may be a duplex stream.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If required, you can access the raw connection underlying the request via `request.socket`, which is guaranteed to be an instance of `<net.Socket>` unless the user specified another socket type.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Stops the server from accepting new connections and closes all connections connected to this server which are not sending a request or waiting for a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Closes all established HTTP(S) connections connected to this server, including active connections connected to this server which are sending a request or waiting for a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This does *not* destroy sockets upgraded to a different protocol, such as WebSocket or HTTP/2.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This is a forceful way of closing all connections and should be used with caution.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Whenever using this in conjunction with `server.close`, calling this *after* `server.close` is recommended as to avoid race conditions where new connections are created between a call to this and a call to `server.close`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Closes all connections connected to this server which are not sending a request or waiting for a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Starting with Node.js 19.0.0, there's no need for calling this method in conjunction with `server.close` to reap `keep-alive` connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Using it won't cause any harm though, and it can be useful to ensure backwards compatibility for libraries and applications that need to support versions older than 19.0.0.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Limit the amount of time the parser will wait to receive the complete HTTP headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If the timeout expires, the server responds with status 408 without forwarding the request to the request listener and then closes the connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It must be set to a non-zero value (e.g.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] 120 seconds) to protect against potential Denial-of-Service attacks in case the server is deployed without a reverse proxy in front.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Starts the HTTP server listening for connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method is identical to `server.listen()` from `net.Server`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sets the timeout value in milliseconds for receiving the entire request from the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Sets the timeout value for sockets, and emits a `'timeout'` event on the Server object, passing the socket as an argument, if a timeout occurs.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If there is a `'timeout'` event listener on the Server object, then it will be called with the timed-out socket as an argument.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] By default, the Server does not timeout sockets.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] However, if a callback is assigned to the Server's `'timeout'` event, timeouts must be handled explicitly.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The maximum number of requests socket can handle before closing keep alive connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] When the limit is reached it will set the `Connection` header value to `close`, but will not actually close the connection, subsequent requests sent after the limit is reached will get `503 Service Unavailable` as a response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The number of milliseconds of inactivity before a socket is presumed to have timed out.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] A value of `0` will disable the timeout behavior on incoming connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The socket timeout logic is set up on connection, so changing this value only affects new connections to the server, not any existing connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The number of milliseconds of inactivity a server needs to wait for additional incoming data, after it has finished writing the last response, before a socket will be destroyed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] A value of `0` will disable the keep-alive timeout behavior on incoming connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] A value of `0` makes the HTTP server behave similarly to Node.js versions prior to 8.0.0, which did not have a keep-alive timeout.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] An additional buffer time added to the `server.keepAliveTimeout` to extend the internal socket timeout.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This buffer helps reduce connection reset (`ECONNRESET`) errors by increasing the socket timeout slightly beyond the advertised keep-alive timeout.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This option applies only to new incoming connections.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Calls `server.close()` and returns a promise that fulfills when the server has closed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This object is created internally by an HTTP server, not by the user.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It is passed as the second parameter to the `'request'` event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Indicates that the response is completed, or its underlying connection was terminated prematurely (before the response completion).
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Emitted when the response has been sent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] More specifically, this event is emitted when the last segment of the response headers and body have been handed off to the operating system for transmission over the network.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] It does not imply that the client has received anything yet.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method adds HTTP trailing headers (a header but at the end of the message) to the response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Trailers will **only** be emitted if chunked encoding is used for the response; if it is not (e.g. if the request was HTTP/1.0), they will be silently discarded.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] HTTP requires the `Trailer` header to be sent in order to emit trailers, with a list of the header fields in its value.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Attempting to set a header field name or value that contains invalid characters will result in a `TypeError` being thrown.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] This method signals to the server that all of the response headers and body have been sent; that server should consider this message complete.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The method, `response.end()`, MUST be called on each response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `data` is specified, it is similar in effect to calling `response.write(data, encoding)` followed by `response.end(callback)`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] If `callback` is specified, it will be called when the response stream is finished.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The `response.finished` property will be `true` if `response.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] Reads out a header that's already been queued but not sent to the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p01] The object returned by the `response.getHeaders()` method *does not* prototypically inherit from the JavaScript `Object`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] True if headers were sent, false otherwise.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] A reference to the original HTTP `request` object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] When true, the Date header will be automatically generated and sent in the response if it is not already present in the headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This should only be disabled for testing; the Date header is required in most HTTP responses (see RFC 9110 Section 6.6.1 for details).
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Sets a single header value for implicit headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Therefore, `response.getHeader()` may return non-string values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] However, the non-string values will be converted to strings for network transmission.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If `response.writeHead()` method is called and this method has not been called, it will directly write the supplied header values onto the network channel without caching internally, and the `response.getHeader()` on the header will not yield the expected result.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If progressive population of headers is desired with potential future retrieval and modification, use `response.setHeader()` instead of `response.writeHead()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Sets the Socket's timeout value to `msecs`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If a callback is provided, then it is added as a listener on the `'timeout'` event on the response object.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If no `'timeout'` listener is added to the request, the response, or the server, then sockets are destroyed when they time out.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If a handler is assigned to the request, the response, or the server's `'timeout'` events, timed out sockets must be handled explicitly.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] After response header was sent to the client, this property indicates the status code which was sent out.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] When using implicit headers (not calling `response.writeHead()` explicitly), this property controls the status message that will be sent to the client when the headers get flushed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] After response header was sent to the client, this property indicates the status message which was sent out.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If set to `true`, Node.js will check whether the `Content-Length` header value and the size of the body, in bytes, are equal.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Mismatching the `Content-Length` header value will result in an `Error` being thrown, identified by `code:` `'ERR_HTTP_CONTENT_LENGTH_MISMATCH'`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Is `true` after `response.end()` has been called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This property does not indicate whether the data has been flushed, for this use `response.writableFinished` instead.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If this method is called and `response.writeHead()` has not been called, it will switch to implicit header mode and flush the implicit headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This sends a chunk of the response body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This method may be called multiple times to provide successive parts of the body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If `rejectNonStandardBodyWrites` is set to true in `createServer` then writing to the body is not allowed when the request method or response status do not support content.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If an attempt is made to write to the body for a HEAD request or as part of a `204` or `304`response, a synchronous `Error` with the code `ERR_HTTP_BODY_NOT_ALLOWED` is thrown.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If `chunk` is a string, the second parameter specifies how to encode it into a byte stream.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] `callback` will be called when this chunk of data is flushed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This is the raw HTTP body and has nothing to do with higher-level multi-part body encodings that may be used.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The first time `response.write()` is called, it will send the buffered header information and the first chunk of the body to the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The second time `response.write()` is called, Node.js assumes data will be streamed, and sends the new data separately.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] That is, the response is buffered up to the first chunk of the body.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Sends an HTTP/1.1 100 Continue message to the client, indicating that the request body should be sent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] See the `'checkContinue'` event on `Server`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Sends an HTTP/1.1 103 Early Hints message to the client with a Link header, indicating that the user agent can preload/preconnect the linked resources.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The `hints` is an object containing the values of headers to be sent with early hints message.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The optional `callback` argument will be called when the response message has been written.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The status code is a 3-digit HTTP status code, like `404`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The last argument, `headers`, are the response headers.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Optionally one can give a human-readable `statusMessage` as the second argument.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] `headers` may be an `Array` where the keys and values are in the same list.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] So, the even-numbered offsets are key values, and the odd-numbered offsets are the associated values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The array is in the same format as `request.rawHeaders`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This method must only be called once on a message and it must be called before `response.end()` is called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If `response.write()` or `response.end()` are called before calling this, the implicit/mutable headers will be calculated and call this function.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] When headers have been set with `response.setHeader()`, they will be merged with any headers passed to `response.writeHead()`, with the headers passed to `response.writeHead()` given precedence.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If this method is called and `response.setHeader()` has not been called, it will directly write the supplied header values onto the network channel without caching internally, and the `response.getHeader()` on the header will not yield the expected result.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] `Content-Length` is read in bytes, not characters.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Node.js will check whether `Content-Length` and the length of the body which has been transmitted are equal or not.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Sends an arbitrary HTTP/1.1 1xx informational response to the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This is a generic equivalent of `response.writeContinue()`, `response.writeProcessing()` and `response.writeEarlyHints()`, and can be called multiple times before the final response.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] After the final response headers have been sent (via `response.writeHead()` or an implicit header), calling this method throws `ERR_HTTP_HEADERS_SENT`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Sends an HTTP/1.1 102 Processing message to the client, indicating that the request body should be sent.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] An `IncomingMessage` object is created by `http.Server` or `http.ClientRequest` and passed as the first argument to the `'request'` and `'response'` event respectively.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] It may be used to access response status, headers, and data.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Different from its `socket` value which is a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`, the `IncomingMessage` itself extends `<stream.Readable>` and is created separately to parse and emit the incoming HTTP headers and payload, as the underlying socket may be reused multiple times in case of keep-alive.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Emitted when the request has been aborted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Emitted when the request has been completed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Check `message.destroyed` from `<stream.Readable>`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The `message.aborted` property will be `true` if the request has been aborted.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The `message.complete` property will be `true` if a complete HTTP message has been received and successfully parsed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Calls `destroy()` on the socket that received the `IncomingMessage`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If `error` is provided, an `'error'` event is emitted on the socket and `error` is passed as an argument to any listeners on the event.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Key-value pairs of header names and values.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] To allow duplicate values of the headers listed above to be joined, use the option `joinDuplicateHeaders` in `http.request()` and `http.createServer()`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] See RFC 9110 Section 5.3 for more information.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] For duplicate `cookie` headers, the values are joined together with `;`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] For all other headers, the values are joined together with `,`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] In case of server request, the HTTP version sent by the client.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] In the case of client response, the HTTP version of the connected-to server.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Also `message.httpVersionMajor` is the first integer and `message.httpVersionMinor` is the second.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The raw request/response headers list exactly as they were received.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The keys and values are in the same list.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The raw request/response trailer keys and values exactly as they were received.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Calls `message.socket.setTimeout(msecs, callback)`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] An `<AbortSignal>` that is aborted when the underlying socket closes or the request is destroyed.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The signal is created lazily on first access — no `<AbortController>` is allocated for requests that never use this property.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The `net.Socket` object associated with the connection.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] With HTTPS support, use `request.socket.getPeerCertificate()` to obtain the client's authentication details.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This property is guaranteed to be an instance of the `<net.Socket>` class, a subclass of `<stream.Duplex>`, unless the user specified a socket type other than `<net.Socket>` or internally nulled.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] The HTTP response status message (reason phrase).
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Similar to `message.trailers`, but there is no join logic and the values are always arrays of strings, even for headers received just once.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This contains only the URL that is present in the actual HTTP request.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] To parse the URL into its parts:new URL(`http://${process.env.HOST ??
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] When `request.url` is `'/status?name=ryan'` and `process.env.HOST` is undefined:$ node > new URL(`http://${process.env.HOST ??
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Ensure that you set `process.env.HOST` to the server's host name, or consider replacing this part entirely.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] If using `req.headers.host`, ensure proper validation is used, as clients may specify a custom `Host` header.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] This class serves as the parent class of `http.ClientRequest` and `http.ServerResponse`.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] It is an abstract outgoing message from the perspective of the participants of an HTTP transaction.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Emitted when the buffer of the message is free again.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Emitted when the transmission is finished successfully.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] Emitted after `outgoingMessage.end()` is called.
[src:javascript/api-http-p02] When the event is emitted, all data has been processed but not necessarily completely flushed.
